(287, 60, '_form', '<div class=\"intro\"> \n<p>A problem analysis helps to identify what the main problems are, along with their root causes and their effects or consequences. This information is critical in determining what the purpose and goals of your organisation should be.</p>\n<p><i>Below are two forms you can use to brainstorm potential problems with your stakeholders. Select <b>Save</b> when you are finished.</i></p>\n<p><b>Solicit input from all key stakeholders</b></p>\n<p>A problem analysis should be carried out in partnership with the key stakeholder groups that were identified in your stakeholder analysis. Without stakeholders’ views about an issue, the nature of the problem, the needs and the solutions will not be clear.</p>\n<p>Be sure that the needs of <b>all</b> people with disabilities are considered, including those most at risk of exclusion (e.g. women with disabilities, people with psychosocial disabilities, refugees with disabilities, etc).</p>\n<p>A workshop is a useful way to carry out a problem analysis with stakeholders, and helps to build a shared sense of understanding, purpose and action. However, it should be noted that it may be necessary to carry out several workshops with different stakeholder groups to ensure that more vulnerable groups are able to express their opinions freely.\n</p>\n<p>Be sure to invite all of the stakeholder groups identified in the stakeholder analysis:</p>\n\n[checkbox checkbox-195 id:checkbox1 class:vertical use_label_element \"People with disabilities and their families\"]<br>\n[checkbox checkbox-196 id:checkbox2 class:vertical use_label_element \"Community members\"]<br>\n[checkbox checkbox-197 id:checkbox3 class:vertical use_label_element \"Representatives of civil society\"]<br>\n[checkbox checkbox-198 id:checkbox4 class:vertical use_label_element \"Government representatives\"]<br>\n[checkbox checkbox-199 id:checkbox5 class:vertical use_label_element \"CBR staff members\"]<br>\n[checkbox checkbox-200 id:checkbox6 class:vertical use_label_element \"CBR managers\"]<br>\n[checkbox checkbox-201 id:checkbox7 class:vertical use_label_element \" Disabled people’s organizations\"]<br>\n\n[checkbox checkbox-201 id:checkbox7 class:vertical use_label_element \" \"] [textarea textarea-20 rows:2 id:textarea1]<br>\n[checkbox checkbox-202 id:checkbox8 class:vertical use_label_element \" \"] [textarea textarea-20 rows:2 id:textarea1]<br>\n[checkbox checkbox-203 id:checkbox9 class:vertical use_label_element \" \"] [textarea textarea-20 rows:2 id:textarea1]<br>\n<p><b>Tools to use when identifying problems</b></p>\n<p>Below are two tools you can use to record problems that are generated during your workshop(s).</p>\n<p><b>Appreciative inquiry</b></p>\n<p>The appreciative inquiry process starts by looking at what a community is good at. The process often begins by asking a question that aims to discover something positive that can be used to build on, such as “Remember a time when people in this community came together to make something really special happen?”</p>\n<p>The 4 steps in the appreciative inquiry process are shown below:</p>\n\n<div class=\"rTable\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\n<div class=\"rTableRow\">\n<div class=\"rTableHead\" style=\"width: 300px;\"><strong>Step</strong></div>\n<div class=\"rTableHead\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Notes</span></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"rTableRow\">\n<div class=\"rTableCell vertical\"><b>1. Discover</b>\n(something that works well)</div>\n<div class=\"rTableCell vertical \">[textarea textarea-183 id:textarea3]<br/></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"rTableRow\">\n<div class=\"rTableCell vertical\"><b>2. Dream</b>\n(how things can continue to work well – or work better – in the future)</div>\n<div class=\"rTableCell vertical \">[textarea textarea-184 id:textarea4]<br/></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"rTableRow\">\n<div class=\"rTableCell vertical\"><b>3. Design</b>\n(plan and prioritize things that work well)</div>\n<div class=\"rTableCell vertical \">[textarea textarea-185 id:textarea5]<br/></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"rTableRow\">\n<div class=\"rTableCell vertical\"><b>4. Do</b>\n(implement the design)</div>\n<div class=\"rTableCell vertical \">[textarea textarea-186 id:textarea6]<br/></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p><b>Problem tree</b></p>\n<p>A problem tree provides you with a way to visualize a problem in diagram form. Enter</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <b>effects</b> of a problem on top, and\n</li>\n<li>The problem’s <b>causes</b> at the bottom\n</li>\n\n<button type=\"submit\" value=\"Submit\">Save</button>\n      <button type=\"reset\" value=\"Reset\">Print</button>\n</div>'),
